    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_436071049" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/436071049" />
    <a title="Joseph" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12914065-joseph"><img alt="Joseph" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450740170p2/12914065.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/436071049?book_show_action=true">Oct 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joseph" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joseph" href="/user/show/12914065-joseph">Joseph</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer436071049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5664210880597640714">The prose is outstanding, the descriptions beautiful, the politics in France and Romanticisms captured well, as are the unique themes deep throughout the novel about sentimentality. One of the few works of fiction that teaches, without lecturing, about the problem of just being ordinary. Frédéric and the other characters are hardly worth caring about on the surface, but I found myself still involved in reading to find the outcome. Also, structurally, Flaubert weaves in and out of time transition</span>
  <span id="freeText5664210880597640714" style="display:none">The prose is outstanding, the descriptions beautiful, the politics in France and Romanticisms captured well, as are the unique themes deep throughout the novel about sentimentality. One of the few works of fiction that teaches, without lecturing, about the problem of just being ordinary. Frédéric and the other characters are hardly worth caring about on the surface, but I found myself still involved in reading to find the outcome. Also, structurally, Flaubert weaves in and out of time transitions so effortlessly that one does not even notice that five years have gone by. The ending is quite intriguing and surprising - a scene most writers probably wouldn’t dare to do, and yet with close reading, it is profound and hits the nail on the head on the sentimentality warning theme tightly focused throughout this amazing work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5664210880597640714" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


